$ mountvol.exe

*Mount Volume Utility*

`mountvol.exe` creates, deletes, or lists a volume mount point.

Some settings, also about devices that had been plugged in in the past, are stored in the → Windows/registry under the → Windows/registry/tree-structure/key
→ Windows/registry/tree/HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE/System/MountedDevices[`HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SYSTEM\MountedDevices`]. These settings can be removed from the registry with `mountvol /r`.

table { ll
`mountvol [drive:]path VolumeName` ☰
`mountvol [drive:]path /D` ☰ Removes the volume mount point from the specified directory.
`mountvol [drive:]path /L` ☰ Lists the mounted volume name for the specified directory.
`mountvol [drive:]path /P` ☰ Removes the volume mount point from the specified directory, dismounts the volume, and makes the volume not mountable. You can make the volume mountable again by creating a volume mount point.
`mountvol /R` ☰ Removes volume mount point directories and registry settings for volumes that are no longer in the system
`mountvol /N` ☰ Disables automatic mounting of new volumes.
`mountvol /E` ☰ Re-enables automatic mounting of new volumes
`mountvol drive: /S` ☰ Mount the → hardware/UEFI/ESP[EFI System Partition] on the given drive.
table }

{ Mounting the EFI System Partition #mountvol-EFI

 `mountvol … /s` mounts the → hardware/UEFI/ESP[EFI System Partition].

code {
C:\> mountvol z: /s
C:\> dir z:\EFI
code }

